== Introduction
A key role of a clinical prosthetist is to manually adjust  and align prosthetic componentry to ensure it functions effectively for the patient's daily activities @jonkergouwEffectAlignmentChanges2016 @hashimotoProperSequenceDynamic2023 @kobayashiEffectProstheticAlignment2014. Proper prosthetic alignment is critical to patient comfort, satisfaction, and overall health, yet fit and function remain common sources of dissatisfaction among prosthesis users @baldockDetectingInteradjustmentCoupling2025. Misalignment is also associated with gait deviations that can lead to back pain and secondary musculoskeletal conditions @zhangEffectProstheticAlignment2019 @gaileyReviewSecondaryPhysical2008 @rabagoPrevalenceGaitDeviations2016. In clinical practice, optimal prosthetic alignment is typically achieved using an iterative process involving visual gait analysis and user feedback @hashimotoProperSequenceDynamic2023 @kobayashiEffectProstheticAlignment2014. Prosthetists leverage known relationships between alignment variables and the resultant biomechanics in order to finetune the overall alignment @adamczykSensitivityBiomechanicalOutcomes2017 @koehler-mcnicholasBiomechanicalResponsePersons2016 @zhangEffectProstheticAlignment2019 @kobayashiEffectProstheticAlignment2014. For instance, if the prosthetic forefoot does not seem stiff enough, a prosthetist may plantarflex the foot to improve midstance stability. Similarly, if the pelvis is tilted in the frontal plane during standing, the prosthetist may adjust the prosthesis length to restore pelvic symmetry. While visual assessment of patient biomechanics is central to this process, observational analysis alone may not be completely accurate, highlighting the need for more objective methods of alignment evaluation in clinical settings @hashimotoProperSequenceDynamic2023 @olaya-miraMethodsAssessLower2025.  

Quantitative motion analysis offers a means of providing prosthetists with objective data to augment decision making @gardUseQuantitativeGait2006 @gageGaitAnalysisProsthetics @wonScopingReviewEvaluate2022. Marker-based motion capture is often used in specialized clinics and research environments to obtain accurate kinematic data, but widespread clinical adoption is limited by cost, time, expertise, and infrastructure requirements @colyerReviewEvolutionVisionBased2018 @itoMarkerlessMotionCapture2022 @simonQuantificationHumanMotion2004. Recent advances in computer vision have facilitated the development of markerless motion capture software that reconstruct human movement using only standard video cameras, thus eliminating the need for markers, expensive motion capture cameras, and specialized software @uhlrichOpenCapHumanMovement2023 @kankoConcurrentAssessmentGait2021 @nakanoEvaluation3DMarkerless2020. These systems show high promise for clinical use, allowing convenient and non-invasive measurement of human movement outside the laboratory environment @lamSystematicReviewApplications2023 @mundermannEvolutionMethodsCapture2006. 

Typical multi-view markerless motion capture pipelines share several core components: synchronized video acquisition, camera calibration to estimate camera intrinsics and extrinsics, pose estimation to detect 2D anatomical keypoints in an image, and 3D reconstruction of the data. Pose estimation, in particular, is a computer vision task that detects the location of specific points of interest in an image (usually referred to as keypoints). In human pose estimation software, these keypoints tend to be major joint centers. For clinical purposes, the choice of pose estimation software is a crucial consideration. Most widely used pose estimation models are trained on datasets comprised primarily of able-bodied individuals (e.g. MediaPipe, which is trained on COCO @linMicrosoftCOCOCommon2015). As a result, their performance may suffer when applied to populations with altered limb morphology, such as limb amputations. Zhou et al. reported substantial errors in joint coordinates and kinematics when applying OpenPose to individuals with lower-limb prostheses @zhouDiffusionModelsEnable2025. Similarly, Cimorelli et al. found that an MMPose algorithm trained on COCO struggled to track prosthetic features in monocular gait analysis, which they addressed by training a custom DeepLabCut model on manually annotated joint locations @cimorelliPortableInclinicVideobased2022. 

Tools such as DeepLabCut (DLC) @mathisDeepLabCutMarkerlessPose2018 allow researchers to train custom pose estimation models using manually labeled images. However, integrating these models into a markerless motion capture pipeline requires software architecture that supports interchangeable pose estimation backends, and many available markerless systems are built around a single pose estimation backbone, limiting their ability to substitute or compare algorithms that might be better suited to specific populations or research needs.

The Free Motion Capture Project (FreeMoCap) @queenFreeMoCapFreeOpen2024 is a free, open-source software package that reconstructs 3D kinematic data from synchronized videos recorded with consumer-grade USB webcams. The base FreeMoCap pipeline estimates 2D body keypoints using MediaPipe @lugaresiMediaPipeFrameworkBuilding2019, performs multi-view triangulation using a modified implementation of the Anipose toolkit @AniposeToolkitRobust2021, and reconstructs 3D joint trajectories. Prior work has demonstrated that FreeMoCap can achieve strong agreement with marker-based systems for spatiotemporal gait parameters @dariciLowCostMarkerlessMotion2025a ($R^2 > 0.90$, RMSE < 3cm), and can detect changes in sagittal-plane joint mechanics during gait from controlled postural manipulations in healthy adults @nunez-lisboaUnderstandingGaitAlterations2024. Here, we evaluate the accuracy and sensitivity of a FreeMoCap-based system in detecting changes in gait and 3D kinematics resulting from controlled prosthesis alignment changes. We leverage the modular architecture of the software to integrate two alternative pose estimation backends: RTMPose @jiangRTMPoseRealTimeMultiPerson2023 and a custom-trained DLC model optimized for prosthetic keypoint detection. 

The primary contributions of this work are threefold. First, we compare three pose estimation backends - two that operate out-of-the-box (MediaPipe and RTMPose) and one requiring modest manual annotation (DeepLabCut) - in their ability to track prosthetic limb pose within a markerless motion capture pipeline. Second, we leverage three controlled, clinically standard prosthetic alignment adjustments (leg length, sagittal plane ankle angle, and toe-in/toe-out) as ground truth perturbations to evaluate system sensitivity. Third, we assess whether the system can capture clinically meaningful biomechanical consequences of these adjustments, including joint kinematics, minimum toe clearance, and pelvic obliquity. Together, these contributions provide a framework for extending markerless motion capture to populations with atypical limb morphology, with direct implications for objective prosthetic alignment assessment in clinical settings. 
